#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/CrossOriginStorage.rst:302
msgid "Custom ``Module['instantiateWasm']`` implementations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/CrossOriginStorage.rst:304
msgid ""
"The COS fetch logic described above lives inside ``instantiateAsync()``, "
"which is the standard Emscripten wasm loading path.  When a program provides "
"its own ``Module['instantiateWasm']`` callback, Emscripten calls that "
"callback directly and **skips** ``instantiateAsync()`` entirely, so the "
"built-in COS code is never reached."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/CrossOriginStorage.rst:310
msgid ""
"To support COS in a custom loader, Emscripten exposes the build-time SHA-256 "
"hash as a named Module property:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/CrossOriginStorage.rst:317
msgid ""
"This property is set by the generated JavaScript before "
"``Module['instantiateWasm']`` is called, so it is always available inside "
"the callback.  ``Module`` in this context is the config object passed to the "
"module factory — whatever variable you use when calling ``new "
"Module(config)`` or the equivalent factory function.  A custom loader can "
"read ``Module['wasmHash']`` via a reference to that config object:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/CrossOriginStorage.rst:361
msgid ""
"``Module['wasmHash']`` is only present in builds compiled with :ref:"
"`CROSS_ORIGIN_STORAGE`.  Always guard on its truthiness before using it, as "
"shown above, so the same loader code works in builds compiled without the "
"flag."
msgstr ""

